Analysis by Edward Luttwak published by the Hoover Institution (Sept 21). If I understand his thesis correctly, the only war termination strategy that achieves "the most durable form of peace" is exhausting the material resources and manpower necessary to keep fighting." He makes the case that neither country will run out of manpower at current rates and that only Ukraine can run out of materiel resources if left to its own devices. But since it appears the "United States has seemingly added Ukraine’s sustainment to its other entitlement programs", Ukraine won't run out of materiel resources either. So how will the war end? I think he says it must end by a negotiated settlement, an unsatisfactory way to end. When will it end? Could be a pretty long time from now: "... to hope for Putin’s fall is not a strategy." https://www.hoover.org/research/our-twenty-first-century-eighteenth-century-war

Russian military is making minor advances and digging extensive protective positions. Most probable outcome in the near term is stalemate as Ukrainian forces generally lack the sorts of brekatrhough weapons including air power that would be required to take back substantive territory as has recently been shown in Kherson front. Stalemate outcomes are historically very difficult to resolve through negotiation when they involve territory - this has been true between Israel and Syria (no final status agreement) India and Pakistan and Ukraine and Russia since 2014.

There is no evidence of coordination between the European Union’s (EU) three biggest powers last week, but it is striking that they made such similar comments. These began when President Emmanuel Macron stated on May 9 that Ukraine would not join the EU for decades and that the war must not end in “humiliation.” Four days later, Chancellor Olaf Scholz spoke to Putin and called for a ceasefire, while Italy’s premier Mario Draghi echoed that call after meeting President Biden. Notably, the US President did not support those comments, and Ukraine’s President Volodymyr Zelenskyy responded sharply, saying Macron was seeking to save Russia’s face.

As many others have pointed out, there is no win available for Putin at this point. If he is pushed out of Ukraine, he has obviously lost but even if he were to capture large chunks or all of it, it will be an occupying force and not easily held to say nothing of how Russia would be treated by the rest of the world. Putin buzzed past off-ramps early on and now there are no more ramps, just a long road to nowhere. And in this current scenario, the status quo favors Putin. It gives Ukraine and the rest of the world time to make a diplomatic mistake that Putin can use to justify something. Meanwhile, Ukraine and the rest of the world are waiting for the Russian people to grow weary of the war and for Putin's delusions to be widely recognized. And therefore the current stalemate of effectively each side waiting for the other to make a mistake will continue.
There is too much fight left in both for an early resolution.

I start by looking at the lengths of other conflicts, helpfully provided by Wikipedia. In the last 50 years, 4/24 *completed* conflicts terminated in under 7 months (the time from the moment of my forecast to the final timeline of the question). Of the last 10 conflicts, only 2 completed within that timeline. This leads me to believe that the war is likely to drag on past 1 Dec 2022. If I include *ongoing* conflicts (excluding Russia-Ukraine), just 4/39 have completed within that timeline in the last 50 years, and only 1/10 of the last 10 conflicts have completed within that timeline.
